data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14 (.NET 10), new **span overload resolution rules** cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime (or may fail at compile time depending on context).

## Fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches ensure the compiler selects the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which is representable in expression trees and works with the interpreted compiler.
